We wanted to build a suite of unit tests for our session beans.  We looked at Cactus and played with it a bit and were put off by some of the effort involved in making it work.  You have to address various client vs server deployment issues, it seems confusiong wrt what code is executed in the client vs the server ,etc.

We decided not to devote that level of effort to Cactus just yet and instead are writing unit tests that act as clients to the session beans and testing them in that manner using the normal test runner.

It&#39;s not clear to me what the disadvantages are to this approach.  Comments?

John

-----Original Message-----
From: Jeff Nielsen [mailto:jeff.nielsen@...]
Sent: Tuesday, April 01, 2003 9:16 PM
To: junit@yahoogroups.com
Subject: Re: [junit] Junit and EJBs


Here our some suggestions based on the way we test our EJB code.

1. Test all of the logic in the code outside of the container.  For example,
your actual EJB class can delegate all of the processing to a handler, which
can be instantiated directly by the test.

2. Use the &quot;Cactus&quot; add-on to JUnit to write/run in-container tests that
exercise the EJB plumbing.  Then you can just use HTTP for the test runner
to communicate with the EJB container, which is less of a hassle.


